section16:
  "Now, to finish the topic off, we’ll get started with a short quiz section!"
  if (< $data.points 5):
    jump section17
  else:
    jump section23

//EASY PATH
section17:
  choice:
    "Q1: Which of the following is not a support level for individuals with ASD?"
    "Level 1":
      set data.answerQ17 false
      jump section18
    "Level 2":
      set data.answerQ17 false
      jump section18
    "Level 3":
      set data.answerQ17 false
      jump section18
    "Level 4":
      set data.answerQ17 true
      jump section18

section18:
  if (== $data.answerQ17 true):
    add data.points 1
    "That's correct!"
  else:
    add data.points -3 //since getting this wrong means you haven't been paying attention At All
    "Unfortunately that's wrong :("
    "The Support Level system uses the Levels 1, 2 and 3. Level 4 does not exist."
  jump section19

section19:
  choice:
    "Q2: True or False: Are support levels solely based on an individual's intellectual abilities?"
    "True":
      set data.answerQ19 false
      jump section20
    "False":
      set data.answerQ19 true
      jump section20

section20:
  if (== $data.answerQ18 true):
    add data.points 1
    "That's correct!"
  else:
    add data.points -1
    "Unfortunately that's wrong :("
  "Support Levels are based on a multitude of axis, which includes intellectual abilities among many. Other factors include language capability, social skills, sensory sensitivity, restriction in behaviour and so on."
  jump section21

section21:
  choice:
    "Q3: Which support level would most likely describe an individual with ASD who requires a moderate amount of support across most environments?"
    "Level 1":
      set data.answerQ21 false
      jump section22
    "Level 2":
      set data.answerQ21 true
      jump section22
    "Level 3":
      set data.answerQ21 false
      jump section22

section22:
  if (== $data.answerQ21 true):
    add data.points 1
    "That's correct!"
  else:
    add data.points -1
    "Unfortunately that's wrong :("
  "Someone who requires a moderate level of support across most enviroments, will struggle to live their life to the fullest extent without consistent support. They will require more supervision and care than someone with level 1 support needs. Still they regain more independence than those with level 3 support needs, and would be able to work without external help in certain enviroments."
  jump section28

//HARD PATH
section23:
  "Since you did pretty well so far, we’ll give you some harder questions!"
  choice:
    "Q1: Which of the following would <em>not</em> be considered when determining an autistic persons’ support level?"
    "Communication Skills":
      set data.answerQ23 false
      jump section24
    "Language Skills":
      set data.answerQ23 false
      jump section24
    "Sensory Sensitivities":
      set data.answerQ23 false
      jump section24
    "Age of Diagnosis":
      set data.answerQ23 true
      jump section24

section24:
  if (== $data.answerQ23 true):
    add data.points 2
    "That's correct!"
  else:
    add data.points -2
    "Unfortunately that's wrong :("
  "Some autistic people are diagnosed later in life than others, some even only in adulthood. This does not mean however that someone who is diagnosed later in life would automatically have lower support needs, or someone diagnosed early higher support needs. Autism is difficult to diagnose, and often comes with comorbidties like ADHD which makes diagnosis diffiuclt. Furthermore, childhood trauma can impact how much someone struggles with their autistic symptoms when growing up, or even cause misdiagnosis until much later in life."
  "If a colleague talks about how they were diagnosed well out of early childhood (as is typical), this is not a sign that they don't need substantial support because 'they could manage before'. Please be mindful about what you assume about those around you."
  jump section25

section25:
